The Prague Stock Exchange plunges into the negative against the close of business.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with ČEZ's shares reached nearly half of normal day-to-day business.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued to build on Monday's slump right at the start of Tuesday's deals, when it fell by a further six percentage points.
This time, the reason for the slump was on Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilization plan for the financial sector there, is also evident.
Case of shares in Asia
The shares on the stock exchanges in Asia experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the indices were able to make up for some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng Stock Exchange's index in Hong Kong lost nearly four percentage points over the course of the business day, but was later able to make up for some of the losses, thus reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which observes the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
Shares on the Sydney stock exchange lost more than five per cent, but then decreased losses to 4.3 per cent.
Taiwan's stock market fell 3.6 percent, according to the index there.
"The timing for the U.S. bailout is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide," according to Hong Kong's chief executive Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independent of China's central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
American lawmakers should, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, return to the negotiating table as soon as possible, and pass the draft for support for the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that other countries would also be affected by the slump.
A bloodbath of American stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan for support for the financial system, for which up to $700 billion (nearly Kč $12 trillion) should be spent.
Lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
In Bush’s view, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices recorded the biggest slump in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell by almost seven percent, a similar slump it had last recorded in 1987.
The index had already dropped before the vote, but there were hardly any signs that the draft would not get through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concession: U.S. government allowed to pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of the American Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush has agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial assistance to the American financial system.
This is to be voted on early next week.
American lawmakers reached a breakthrough in talks on the adoption of a rescue plan in the form of a grant to the American financial system in the amount of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns).
However, this does not mean a victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they are allowed to publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the American Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, Chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee Barney Frank told Reuters.
In the Senate, according to various data, it could probably be voted on the plan on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, a communication that the plan will be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor for a revitalization of financial markets.
After that, however, there is a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms, how to help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our differing views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, there could be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met with the American Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on the night of Sunday to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for a purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from the financial companies, which plunge the financial firms into heavy losses and jeopardize the stability of the entire system.
“We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
You have to continue the recovery plan, but I think we are at our destination," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, the legislators are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
The aim is to calm investors before doing business in the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a decision of Congress could influence the business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not quite clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, and there is also uncertainty about whether the negotiations at the last minute could fail because of a problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be passed in the next few days.
The law, however, will still undergo some changes.
The total amount intended to help the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
Congress, however, can block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program does not perform its function, at another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush values progress in negotiations positively
The president has a veto power in this decision, but Congress can overrule its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has persisted, which was based on gaining finances for the purchase of bad mortgage securities, the value of which has fallen, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
“We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, the Senate then on Monday," according to Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
The American President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and "appreciates the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Restriction of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing off perks and a timetable for funding the plan.
The new law is also intended to restrict the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the program and sets up a committee to supervise the Fund.
This is to be headed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on it and made a big progress toward an agreement that works and is important to the market and to all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also expects help for homeowners who have trouble repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new installments on mortgages it buys up, with the goal being to lower the monthly cost to the debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological Help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to the main economist of Patria Finance David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
“This is because one does not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought.
That will be crucial to how the financial sector and government split the losses among themselves," Marek told the server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be passed now or early next week is not decisive, in Marek's view.
“Much more importantly, congressmen agree to support the plan and that they pass it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on the fact that there is a passing is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, overall they come to 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both parties of the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought after the first preliminary results the early parliamentary elections of Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly severe losses, where the position of the previous chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the decline.
In contrast, the head of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian state governor Jörg Haider, is gearing up for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but it loses 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last elections in 2006.
The ÖVP, which loses almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent, performed even worse.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in post-war Austrian history, and especially with the People's Party, which had demanded the early elections, this is a really disastrous result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP had withdrawn from the coalition, the People's Party had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
The voters, however, have probably punished the party for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there was speculation about a possible resignation of the party chairman and previous Vice Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be the case as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party's executive committee.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the election debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freiheitliche (FPÖ) provisionally received 18 percent, the BZÖ eleven percent of the votes - the Social Democrats at the same time expressed their fear that the year 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party had agreed with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still uniform, in 2005 it had split from the BZÖ) with regard to a common government, which even had made sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Jörg Haider, who already declared that he is ready to work with every party and assumes that he is returning to Austrian federal politics, obviously relies on this development.
In addition, the Green Party moved into parliament, which suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four percent hurdle and therefore did not enter parliament.
