The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be long in coming.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile operators are working among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of a text message here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps taken by the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - for some customers of the Czech mobile phone providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that the prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
The mobile providers, on the other hand, like to scold the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
This is often agreed by the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who had often stated in the past that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of chances (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is one more option - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers on the mobile phone market brought a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile service providers had to react.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices to the market in the UK as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don’t have to look long for examples.
In February this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, among other things.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone conversations and text messages, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in the UK at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to rely on a non-clichéd target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose mobile-making - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav Čepický’s press secretary also doubts this: “The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual suppliers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the range of services."
In the Czech Republic, say the mobile phone providers
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile-making.
“While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very hopeful.
It will be more likely to lead to a market entry of mobile in other countries in our region," says Jana Studničková, press spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, she confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
The GTS Novera Group, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer sector, has been showing its interest in a launch of a virtual mobile network provider for a long time.
“We have a keen interest in providing our customers with not only fixed-line, but also mobile telecommunication services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve negotiation progress," said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Non-official information shows that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
“At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specifics compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area," says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specifics of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Martina Kemrová's press secretary adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "So far, we have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project to continue to build on."
And she adds: "There will be hardly any virtual provider appearing on T-Mobile's network by the end of the year.
At this moment, we would have to have a concrete offer to be able to think in the short term.”
Vodafone is more focused on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we consider from the point of view of customers to be the best.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of the mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would be more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
So why should such a competitor be facilitated market entry?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth around the creation of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure in the direction of ČTÚ came at the moment when U:fon came on the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market was also recently strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the character of the mobile communications market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
However, in view of this approach of mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulators is surprising.
This is not only the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately has the competence to intervene in economic competition in Czech - in contrast to Great Britain and other highly developed countries.
It has exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to this whole problem of his very typical attitude.
“The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract between a mobile operator and a virtual provider via the rental of the necessary infrastructure has been concluded.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa from the ÚOHS's Foreign Relations department in his response to our request.
From representatives of the providers, such a formulation would not be surprising.
This is more than worrying from an authority that should represent consumer interests and, among other things, ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián adds Chalupa: "Abroad, where virtual vendors operate normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
Really shocking about this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile phone providers, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same price of petrol at the gas stations is certainly only coincidence and the consequence of a fierce competition.
“The Authority has not discovered any signs in this matter which indicate action against competition, and therefore it has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so he does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for his actions in the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile phone market to virtual providers are also likely to be lacking for the regulatory authority for telecommunications," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, elaborated by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile providers has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the consent of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile provider has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily assumes a dominant position in a certain segment.
But even if you do not go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile providers are strikingly similar.
Complaints by a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a quite common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to implement in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act the extension of the competences of ČTÚ to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS have to know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's already possible when no one is looking
The functioning of any pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunication services, but these are only partly public.
Usually these are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Our own mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the operator, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will receive special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resale.
"Should there be cases that describe you, then it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to a termination of cooperation with the appropriate society," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be talked about by those responsible for the mobile phone providers.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a course of action.
From the activity of these companies, they do not flow to negligible profits, at the same time - in contrast to the actual virtual providers - they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot have full-fledged it like the normal customers of the mobile providers.
But that alone, the ČTÚ would at least have to seem strange.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
Do the mobile providers turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why do they lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to uncover such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to settle for the explanation of the providers that they know nothing about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasized several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought with it a significant price decline in the various services.
Virtually in all countries, where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their creation practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that the regulatory bodies intervened, which did not attempt to safeguard the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this was followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators throw themselves into the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than favorable in these cases.
But we do not throw the shotgun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile phone provider, the ÚOHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating against) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
