Wednesday, the 1. October 2008, will go down in the history of Prague's public transport companies as a date on which the first passengers board a subway, tram or bus, who carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the chip card Opencard.
Passengers can have a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1. January 2009) and have it installed on their chip card at the same time, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons have also been available via the Internet on the website of the Verkehrsbetriebe www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the Internet sale can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they have so far had to wait regularly in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, it is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, the travellers also have a counter with trained staff available to advise interested parties on the Internet purchase and also play the coupon on the card," said the spokesman for the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, the electronic coupons can also be placed on the opencard at self-service machines, which are installed in some subway vestibules.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket devaluers, the passengers may already have them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská noticed.
"Currently there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year it should be eighty," adds Opatrný.
The coupon inspects a machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
You just have to introduce the chip card, and the previously acquired coupon plays up on its own.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants from municipalities of the Central Bohemians in particular reach the capital.
"In the trains belonging to Prague's integrated traffic, the train attendants have readers with which they can check the validity period of the coupons by time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization the ticket control. This organization compiles the timetables for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the ticket office at the driver's office.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked location on the side of the checkout.
With this, the driver checks the validity of the coupons played.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons played, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal said.
A passenger who does not travel by suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can in turn go to the self-service machines, where the coupons are played on the card.
Here, the information on the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the US
The Sudeten Germans had asked in 1945 for the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States.
This is according to a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would like to live at least under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans are said to have turned to the US president in 1945.
This is according to a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
In the letter, the Germans of Krumau ask the American president not to allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," read a letter signed with the words "people to whom the fate of the Sudeten is dear."
Since the annexation to Czechoslovakia suggests the Sudeten Germans - in the knowledge of the Czech national character - that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to assume the patronage over the Bohemian Forest forever and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you grant this area to a foreign state that oppresses and tries to eliminate minorities and has not contributed anything to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is supposedly the fear of revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US President had doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he would initiate a referendum in the Böhmerwaldgau on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the USA or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today's knowledge of post-war history, it paints a good picture in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses with regard to the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans had to at least suspect that they would negotiate their deportation from the Republic, only a few of them had such a possibility.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Still others believed they could just stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who is from Budweis.
He was employed in the war as a Budweiser German in the Navy on the Baltic Sea.
When he came into British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens more Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would fit them," Chalupa said.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected him to be driven out of the republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
