Olmert would return almost all occupied territories in exchange for peace
The chairman of the provisional Israeli government, Ehud Olmert, has advocated the return of virtually all territories that were occupied in 1967, including the Jordan Country, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, if peace with Palestine and Syria could be made in exchange for it.
This he emphasized in an interview printed on Monday by the daily Jediot Achronot.
"We must reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means it will be necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, if not all," Olmert told the newspaper.
"We retain a certain percentage of these territories, but we will have to cede a similarly high percentage (Israeli territory) to the Palestinians because without this there will be no peace," he added.
He acknowledged that a possible return would also include East Jerusalem.
"The one who wants security in Jerusalem and, above all, does not want tractors or bulldozers to roll over his legs, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to forgo part of Jerusalem," Olmert remarked, alluding to two attacks in the city in July, in which several people were killed and dozens of people injured.
According to the Premier, it will be necessary to find a "special solution for the temple burber and sacred and historical places" that lie on the territory of the Old City.
“The one who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will have to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
This will not work," he continued.
Withdrawal from the Golan heights
Olmert advocated a withdrawal of Israel from the Golan heights, which in his view is an indispensable condition for the conclusion of a peace treaty with Syria.
However, this would also require some effort on the part of Damascus.
"My proposal is not to make peace with Syria solely on the basis of a withdrawal from the Golan Heights," Olmert said.
“The Syrians know all too well what they have to do without to get the Golan Heights back.
They will have to forego their present relationship with Iran; they will have to forego their relationship with the (Shiite) Hezbollah movement; they will have to renounce the constant support they grant to the terrorism of the (Shiite) Hamas movement, the Al-Khaida terrorist network and the jihad (the Holy War) in Iraq," the prime minister said.
