A seabed, larger than the mainland
The neighbouring states today vehemently registered their claim to the new sea areas.
After a UN convention, they make use of their rights, which they agreed on in 1982 in Montego Bay in Jamaica.
It is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often reaches up to a few hundred kilometers from the shore of a country into the sea.
According to the Convention, this country has an exclusive right to all sources of the continental shelf.
“In simple terms, the continental shelf is the part of the seabed and its soles, which represents a natural continuation of the continent below the sea surface.
It crosses the borders of the sea, often also the border of two hundred nautical miles of the so-called exclusive economic zone," explains Mikulka.
The application submitted by the relevant country to the Commission to fix the external borders of the continental shelf must be supported by extensive scientific and technical documentation based on many costly investigations and measurements.
It is the result of many years of preparatory work.
“One of our tasks is to provide technical and technical support to the Commission.
The Commission has so far negotiated over five applications, including Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
Until now, only the latter three countries have had success," adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia was recently met with an international response, which was the first country to significantly increase its sea areas.
Yet New Zealand is also a winner - the stretch of the seabed, which was approved by the Commission to the country last week, is about 1.6 million square kilometres, so about six times more than the size of the actual state.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in the investigations.
The profit that will flow to them in the future from the use of the seabed will, as they promise, have invaluable value.
Other countries will also submit their applications gradually.
They can do this for ten years from the moment they ratify the "Montego Bay Agreement."
Where the continental shelf ends, the area of the ocean floor begins, which is described by the convention as the "common heritage of humanity."
No state has a special position here.
The right to promote in this area is granted by an international institution established by the Convention.
"The seabed is not a gold-digging country," says with some exaggeration Director Mikulka, adding that its "single areas are legally precisely defined and the system is contractually anchored."
Czechs in the Pacific
