Sleepless nights for Hypo Real Estate creditors
The German banking system is relatively stable, stressed German Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück only last week.
How good that the politician used the word "relative" and also weaves in that the German banking sector would not be spared from the crisis-ridden developments.
Because it has now occurred at the weekend.
The Munich-based real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), which is listed on the Dax, receives a billion-dollar loan from a consortium of German banks in order to shield itself from the turmoil in the markets.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the loan aid amounted to up to 35 billion euros.
The Hypo Real Estate only has to pay interest on the part it also takes.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
The background is losses in the daughter Depfa.
According to a newspaper report for long-term projects for which he has lent money, the state financier had refinanced himself at extremely short notice - which is no longer possible because of the mistrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's cash reserve had shrunk by 95 percent to €2.37 million, and the equity ratio had also declined slightly from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Current income and net income from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period of the previous year, income from attributions to receivables and certain securities, and from the resolution of provisions in the lending business by more than 70 percent to EUR 5 million.
Only thanks to higher income from reimbursements of downstream clearing costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group as well as from the reimbursement of interest in accordance with the tax code and from the business procurement for group companies, the earnings decline had still been moderate at around 16 percent.
After his privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially speculated on commercial real estate loans, which had then been spun off in Aareal Bank.
Because it earned too little in the classic state financing, Depfa had then become more involved in infrastructure projects and the financing of joint projects of private investors and the state (private public partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, the Hypo Real Estate must now make depreciation and amortization, which will have a "substantial material effect" on the profit and loss account of the group, it is called quite undetermined.
The fact is that the dividend has been cancelled.
It had already been cut by two-thirds in 2007.
Hypo Real Estate has been a major state and infrastructure financier since the Depfa takeover.
It is more dependent on refinancing in the interbank market than other institutions, as it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of American investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending among banks has once again largely dried up as banks hoard their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs short-term funds for refinancing annually for a part - around 50 billion euros - of Depfa's loan portfolio.
According to Hypo Real Estate, the Group's financing needs are covered with the loan for the foreseeable future and the company is shielded "from the influence of the currently largely inoperable international money markets."
From other sources, it can be heard that thanks to the funds, the refinancing is secured until the end of 2009.
HRE CEO Georg Funke, on the other hand, said that Hypo Real Estate Group would no longer have to take advantage of the money markets for the foreseeable future.
