Rats also have feelings
A rat or a cockroach flees in case of danger does this mean that it also feels fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
But how could you check if they feel the same thing when they behave similarly to us?
The Internet magazine "Edge" has published contributions by famous scientists for several years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far, where we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, since all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and address questions of sensation or, more generally, consciousness, we enter rough terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it turns up dead, flees or attacks.
Humans behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude on a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe in that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the circuits, which are almost always associated with human consciousness, include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its involvement in short-term memory and execution/control functions).
This wide region is much more developed in humans than in the rest of the primates and seems to be completely absent from other creatures.
Thus, at least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man even differs from the other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity is likely to lie in the linguistic nature of man: Since such a large part of his experience is connected to language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, as it may be, probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is difficult to determine what consciousness may look like in other animals.
If, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor, because of the special hardware, can be analyzed on the basis of our own experience, its exploration presents us with great problems.
Most of my remarks refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible in a scientifically way.
One could examine the processes of consciousness of animals without regard to their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially using the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one shifts to the neural correlates of consciousness rather than to the causal mechanisms: both may or may not be identical.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex for the formation of visualization.
What now results for the sensations?
I attribute them to the fact that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we call "fear" is the mental state we find ourselves in when the activity of the immune system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) proves memory.
From this point of view, sensations are closely tied to the regions of the cortex that distinguish primates and especially humans.
Combined with linguistic nature, fine gradations of the sensation arise, because with the help of the words and the grammar we can differentiate and categorize states in order to attribute them to others in addition to ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations arise from more primitive activities in the body feeling regions of the cortex and the brain stem, similar to Jaak Pankseep, which, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it may well be involved in cross-genre sensations.
In theory, I cannot contradict this, but I think it is unproven.
Pankseep argues that what seems to be fearful in rats and people, probably feels like this in both cases: But how can you check whether rats and people feel the same thing if they behave similarly?
A cockroach flees in danger of whether it also feels fear?
In my view, mere similarity in behavior cannot yet prove any equality of experience.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and people have similar brain strains, scrapes, on the other hand, do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem responsible for sensations?
And even if you could prove this for humans: How did you want to prove it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have sensations.
But I don't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore the emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress on the neural level is waving here, provided that the same is measured in rats and people.
Just as I do not research language and consciousness in rats, nor do I know whether they exist.
You may think this is short-sighted, but I'd rather make progress than run against a wall all the time.
I am a practical emotionalist.
