For years, a mysterious phenomenon has caused perplexity in research: dark matter influences the speed of space probes during so-called swing-by-maneuvers.
Experts fear that Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity might not be quite right.
For nearly 18 years, the "Ulysses" spacecraft flew through space.
Because of soon-to-freeze fuel lines, you now face cold death.
Among scientists, a mysterious phenomenon has caused confusion for years - the swing-by anomaly.
The swing-by is a flight maneuver of space probes, in which they gain additional momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as Earth.
This allows the probes to save a lot of fuel.
The European-American research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick as well as the sun probe Ulysses.
What the researchers have been surprising for years, however, is that the missiles do not behave 100 percent as one would expect under the time-honoured law of gravity.
Rather, there are irregularities in speed.
The probes are unexpectedly faster or slower.
Until now, physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They christened him swing-by anomaly.
Some experts fear that even Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, which describes the attraction of matter through a curvature of space, might not be quite right.
American physicist Stephen Adler of the Institute for Advanced Study from Princeton still firmly believes that Einstein was not mistaken, and tries to explain the swing-by anomaly using the so-called dark matter that astronomers in the universe have identified.
"The responsibility of the anomaly could be dark matter, which could also be located very close to Earth," he writes.
Space researchers have only known about the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
It obviously has an attraction, the effect of which on other celestial bodies can be observed.
It itself, on the other hand, is completely invisible, that is, it does not transmit and reflect any electromagnetic radiation, in particular no visible light.
According to the scientists’ calculations, dark matter accounts for a good fifth of the entire mass of the universe.
