Turkey expands diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, European powers were interested in inuring deep into Turkey's hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps within Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed, imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guidebooks are telling you.
The building sits in a ride at the end of the platforms with a tower at every corner of the front and thus looks like some provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building is disintegrating, for example
But once you are inside the vaulted ticket counter, there is no doubt about the grandeur of the project, of which this was the westernmost approach.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Society.
Germany, which was a late advancer in the imperialist game, had to implement its ambitions to dominate the Middle East, by means of a train connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and further out to what today is Saudi Arabia.
Yet Germany's imperialist projects slammed during the First World War.
His railroad tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, generated by the insurmountable limits of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces moved out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, an ammunition train flew into the air, destroying the ornate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly disintegrated, largely passed from the story.
Today, however, this railway line serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and everything east of it, to highlight the expansion of Turkey's diplomatic horizon.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has introduced a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the neighboring regions, generated by the borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
There is now a policy of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian splinter groups Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the key data of this new foreign policy, I have boarded the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara to visit one of the AKP's leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the stepstep of the old world in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail," I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is seen as a new city, for the new secular state project to turn its back on the Ottoman past.
The AKP, however, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity
This has provoked some of the suspicion in the West, particularly in Washington.
A taxi has taken me to the AKP's main office, a custom-made, ultra-modern stone and steel structure, in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle managers in suits, both men and women, met to complete the first deals of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a BlackBerry.
“The goal of the party’s foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exceptional phenomenon," he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
These days, she has to look east and west at the same time.
There would not be either one or the other.
She'd have to do both.
"But certainly Turkey could eventually," I asked, "be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "did not want to have to face this decision."
He then highlighted a point that almost everyone I spoke to here almost routinely said: Turkey’s relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are just as beneficial for Europe and the United States as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, figuratively speaking, Europe as a whole can travel eastwards towards Asia and the Middle East on the same railway tracks.
Back at Hydarpasha's train station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German gentlemen Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East could now, to a large extent, be in the hands of Turkey.
And when I waited at the dock for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe" in those days.
At the time, at least, there did not seem to be much doubt about which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
