Obscure street in city, often forgotten and possibly soon for sale
New York City has thousands of major thoroughfares, avenues, side streets and other bypasses, some of which are famous and others just comfortable.
Still, it's hard even for experienced taxi drivers and longtime locals to tell where Extra Place is, simply because most have never heard of it.
This tiny street is located in the East Village and runs from First Street north between Bowery and Second Avenue without reaching Second Street.
It is 30 feet wide and 120 feet long and looks more like a dusty alley than an actively used thoroughfare.
There are also no road signs.
It is virtually impossible to find them on a standard road map.
This street still has its admirers.
For example, Avalon Bay, a construction company that recently built luxurious buildings on First Street.
It wants to repave Extra Place to create a clean drive-through to the shops and boutiques expected in the new buildings.
Other admirers include the long-standing neighborhood, which says it's fascinated by the short alley, simply because it's one of the remains of the block's past.
Yet the city administration department, which is responsible for protecting and building the residential buildings and is responsible for the street, has no interest in preserving them.
During a meeting of the municipal council's land use committee this month, representatives of the city administration and Avalon Bay drafted a proposal for the construction company's purchase of the road.
Still, the committee prefers that the road remain in the hands of the city, and has asked for a new plan to be put forward in the coming month, according to Susan Stetzer, the district executive in the local council 3.
"Very little space has remained in the possession of the city and we would like Extra Place to continue to belong to the city," she said.
“There could be offers on how to repair and operate the road, what could be done by Avalon, but we also want public access to remain guaranteed.”
Avalon Bay announced a few months ago that it would repave the small street and set up seats designed, among other things, for a cafe to which the company wants to rent out space.
The idea that Avalon Bay could buy the road was first made public during the session this month.
Michele de Milly, a spokeswoman for Avalon Bay, said the company wanted to use the road, but it did not necessarily own it.
"The main concern of the Avalon Bay is to renovate this derelict alley and make it a public meeting place," she said, adding that the city itself had proposed the sale.
Seth Donlin, spokesman for the Department of Building Protection, said it was actually the city's desire to sell the street and stressed that the department's job was to develop rather than manage the real estate.
Compared to its colorful neighborhood The Bowery, Extra Place has retained some of its historical impression.
Some believe that the street got its name in 1802, when a large farm owned by Philip Minthorne was divided between his numerous children and a narrow strip of land was not claimed by anyone.
The back door of the music club CBGB, the punk rock monument that was closed in 2006, opened to Extra Place and the street is certainly most known as the backdrop for the photo on the cover of the album "Rocket to Russia" by Ramones.
The patch was great, said Danny Fields, the manager of the Ramones who had taken the photo in November 1976.
The road was full of scraps, rags and parts of barrels, posters, leaves and ropes.
Some residents, including the bloggers who write about the East Village's gentrification, have rejected the idea of selling Extra Place, with the argument that this public property, as modest as it is, is to remain public.
Others have praised Extra Place as a rarity – a virtually unchanged splinter of the city that should be left alone.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs the blog called "Jeremiah's Disappearing New York" (subtitled "The Book of Lawsuits: A Bitter Nostalgic View of the Dying City"), has published part of the conversation of city history about Extra Place, which was published in The New Yorker magazine in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote at the time: "Extra Place is a small narrow cul-de-sac that remains dark even during the day and is characterized by rusted metal doors of the warehouses, closed windows and weekly newspapers flying past rain gutters ".
With a few exceptions, the street has looked just as recently in one evening.
A rat ran through the back of the street, not far from the door that used to lead to the CBGB, where a more expensive clothing store is now located.
Graffiti could be seen on the walls and an empty beer bottle lay on the floor not far from a fresh bundle of discarded newspapers.
Some passers-by said they had rarely thought about Extra Place, but suggested the road could be somewhat polished up.
Fields, added that in his opinion, some people underestimate the appeal of the street in its current state.
The best years of my life, he said, were in the places that were dark, damp and disgusting.
Debate on bilingual training: Education in English-speaking environment
In this edition of the "Education Watch," Bruce Fuller and Lance T discuss. Izumi the positions of candidates for bilingual training.
Lance T. Izumi, senior research associate in California studies and senior director in the Department of Educational Sciences at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as good as you think: Why the middle class needs a school selection."
Addressing Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama's proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama's campaign mentions that "the likelihood of successfully completing school among African-American and Hispanic students is lower than in white students" - which is true.
To close this performance gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transitional phase in education for those who are learning English first.
Still, the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which puts the emphasis on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take, for example, "Sixth Street Prep," an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
Still, in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent fourth-grade students passed the state exam in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of children from the fourth year of school were rated as good in the English exam.
This amazing success has been achieved by methods other than those favored by Obama.
The Sixth Street school puts its emphasis on review and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that does not tolerate exceptions.
Furthermore, the school practices the approach according to which the training proceeds in an English-speaking environment. That's exactly the point Obama is supposed to keep in mind, according to headmistress Linda Mikels.
This approach attaches importance to the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialist lessons.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me the school had a remarkable success with a student who had only just arrived from Mexico. 12 months later, you would be able to enter the classroom and no longer recognize it.
"It works," she noted, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large proportion of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school's achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within his own party (the national education associations have long supported the idea of bilingual training) and his own consistent support of bilingual training make predictions about Obama's answer uncertain.
While agreeing to the point that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about the legislation aimed at "only English."
Instead, he said, "You are to make sure that your child can speak Spanish."
If Obama actually wants to close the performance gap, he is supposed to carefully consider educational models that work, rather than despise and trivialize them.
Oil price falls as a result of renewed fears about the economy
The price of petroleum fell sharply on Monday due to fears that even the American rescue plan for financial markets might not be enough to revive the economy.
Crude oil futures on the New York trading exchange fell 7 percent to $99.80 a barrel in the morning session.
Since last Monday, the price has dropped by more than $20.
Over the past two weeks, goods markets have been rocked by both the financial turmoil on Wall Street and strong cyclones in the Gulf of Mexico.
After prices peaked from $145.29 per barrel in July, they have fallen to nearly $90 a barrel this month, then rising again, as a result of the huge uncertainty in financial markets.
On Monday, investors have already expressed concern again, although congressional representatives had announced they had agreed on a rescue plan over the weekend that should be the largest in history.
This news was overshadowed by new worries that the financial crisis was far from over.
In the final chapter of the growing crisis, according to a government statement on Monday, Citigroup is to buy up the banking operations of the Wachovia Corporation.
Meanwhile, Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially nationalised the European financial group Fortis.
According to analysts at Barclays Capital, despite the tense negotiations that took place over the weekend and led to a rescue plan, it has apparently failed to revive sentiment in the markets.
As the economic situation continues to deteriorate, it is expected that demand for goods, including oil, will continue to fall.
Analysts at Deutsche Bank have written in a note to investors that the forecasts for global capital markets, interest rates and exchange rates have become extremely uncertain.
We believe, they continue to write, that the goods markets will also be affected.
“From the perspective of the goods markets, we are most concerned about whether the U.S. virus is spreading globally, particularly to China.”
The bank's analysts have revised down their expectations for oil consumption due to weak economic growth for the coming year, and lowered their forecasts for the price of oil and gas for 2009 by 20%.
