The pride and hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the excesses of the theme parks in the vicinity of Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, loud and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first all-black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet sites, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Nowadays it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee are at the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville came to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
