Eatonville is as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's going to miss."
Even today, in a year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation about racial relations, many here continue to be tired of being watched by outsiders.
