It must be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of nearly 2,400 residents, where the poverty rate is twice as high as the national average.
It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and on guard.
And so really the concerns about Eatonville's image actually started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced to the world her hometown in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida tour guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that runs through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Cheeky as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Away from the road to the left," she wrote, "is the brown -white painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always takes care of, although he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and whatever-always-fits-hourly rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
"Zora described things as they were," according to 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls immortalized the Hurston, quoting the men singing songs about her beauty, which was full of sexual allusions.
She added: "Some people didn't like this."
One still remembers Hurtson as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came into town, she mostly did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and dressed in pants, in a city that even today imagines something to her venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, while many despised them.
"People were always glad to see Zora," Mr Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added while rocking in his chair, on a terrace facing to the back, looking out at Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was in all likelihood christened.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books out of print.
Along with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
There was no big memorial service in Eatonville, no public readings on a grand scale.
"I don't think they understood their contribution in the world or their heritage in the least," according to Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography about Hurston published in 2003.
The turnaround came in the 80s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane main street.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of town.
The proposal was put forward when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred to the community.
"In that time, a bunch of white boys often came and they threw oranges and stuff at the away-seated people," Mr. Franklin said.
“There was even a woman who was killed in the process.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request to force integration by describing its decision in the Brown case against the school board as "insulting rather than respecting my race."
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its young people.
"Black kids were used to being embraced - I remember it - you hugged your teacher in the morning and you hugged your teacher in the evening," according to N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group for the protection of the Eatonville community.
That could be sustained so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You didn't hug his white teacher, because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide there," Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped create space for more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who defied prejudice, just as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements such as: "How can anyone refuse the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's nameless tomb and began fighting for the revival of her fame.
Five years later was a much-praised Hurston biography of Robert E. To find Hemenway on the bookshelves, and once again made them a part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came at exactly a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the light of publicity.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began planning a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway animated the city, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, aroused real civic pride," Ms. Nathiri said.
Ms. Boyd put it a little more simply: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the self-image of the city.
There were more and more travelers, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-escore the past.
Eatonville was added to the statewide historical register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
These days, Eatonville is still a special feature in Florida: just 6 miles from Orlando city centre, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It’s 90% black these days.)
Outsiders in search of the story of Eatonville and its importance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, a permit in advance is necessary and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men at field work - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a brave, confident teacher with a penchant for dark red, still fear her shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival was getting bigger, an increased degree of home pride was also born.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire breed: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better, and just as proud, creative and hardworking, silly and mixed as any other racial and peoples group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, the 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who is planning to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or with the police, who, according to him, could use some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who only drive through here will think, "Ah, this city is nothing compared to all the others," Alondra Kenon said the other day on a Sunday after church.
“But when you actually stop and look at its history for a moment, it’s a very beautiful city.”
Here in New York, we are fluent in financial Latin.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newspaper stalls and the massive television screens in Times Square, they wouldn't even realize they're in the middle of a debacle.
You'd never believe that above their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass facades, bankers and hedge fund administrators who have the monopoly in New York, have the worst horror working day every day since the 1929 stock market collapse.
Suppliers are still pushing the metal tea wagons along sidewalks with loud rattles and transporting trays loaded with muffins for the breakfast sessions.
Latinos were still shuffling around between apartments, like human pack animals loaded with around 50 ironed T-shirts hanging on a yoke-like pole lying on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting on food stalls on their sidewalks for their breakfast bagel and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4pm and 7pm.
It didn't feel like a crisis at all until I decided Thursday afternoon to open a new savings account due to all the doomsday talk.
Although I had decided to put my obligatory course on the quiet late afternoon in my JP Morgan Chase headquarters, there were already about 20 people queuing.
Not at the money counters to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk where regular customers order checkbooks, ask tourists for the way to the department store Macy's and where new customers open accounts.
Most of them in front of me, so I later learned from Starr, my "personal bank employee with license," stood in line for the same reason as me.
Unlike me, however, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks, in places from where they commuted, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (a little like a building society), cooperative banks and those local savings banks that have branches only in one state, and say they treat their customers like family.
In the last year, 15 of those banks have quietly gone bust.
Over the past few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion investments, went bankrupt into bankruptcy administration and drove home New Yorkers last Friday over the weekend, Wachovia, another bank that owns $440 billion worth of savings, was looking for a saving buyer.
Fearing another collapse, the office and store employees who were in front of me brought their cash to a bank that is considered a safe haven, a bank responsible for most of the rescue purchases on Wall Street.
Normal New Yorkers have appropriated flowing financial Latin in recent weeks.
A woman who was on the phone in my Chinese regular supermarket made reference to Lehman Brothers, the bank that went bust and its emaciated-looking chief executive Dick Fuld, as if she were blaspheming about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my apartment block's 50-year-old, has come off our usual entertainment topics about Brad and Angelina and my grocery delivery.
"I now have all my savings in money market funds," she told me after my visit to the bank.
“I’ve changed, I’m not going to take any more risk.”
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon was "Death" Handley (obituary on the 11th. September) responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was intended for young people up to 21 years old, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979 were some of us at the end of 20 - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological changer of form) stood for the willingness and ability of the choir to tackle any piece of music presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with a full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often amazing, always exciting and consisted solely thanks to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for the music, which never subsided for years.
How often did Death stop us to "let the music speak for itself."
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all in music.
So it sings!"
His way of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never sovereign but never exuberant.
However high the musical level was, he always demanded an even higher one.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, during which he directed the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the past 40 years, I’ve written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts and I can sincerely say that I’ve never been disappointed by a single one – often inspired by them.
Tod Handley was that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He loathed conductors who, according to his words, simply "peddled with one or two known show horses in the world."
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your obituary for William Woodruff (25. September) you write that "in 1946 he took over the teaching of economic history again at Oxford and in 1950 received a Houblon-Norman research scholarship ... while at the same time studying for a BSc, an MA and a doctoral degree.
This is a conclusion from an author's note in Woodruff's book, "Beyond Nab End," but it's not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry".
He was in the United States in 1950-1951 in the wake of a Houblon-Norman scholarship, and spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953, he left Nottingham and went to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
Muslim graves desecrated during right-wing slide in Austria
Heinz-Christian Strache, a left-winger of the Austrian right-wing Freedom Party of Austria, and Filip Dewinter, a member of the Belgian right-wing Pertei Vlaams Belang, will take on Thursday, the 17th. January 2008, part of a demonstration in Antwerp to represent the organization "Cities against Islamization".
They carry signs in the style of traffic signs on which a mosque is pictured, crossed out with a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of grave desecration at a Muslim cemetery in Austria that saw significant gains in the country's parliamentary election the same weekend on which extreme right-wing parties record significant gains in the country's general election.
On the night of Friday to this morning, more than 90 graves were severely damaged in the cemetery in Traun near Linz in an action organized, according to the police.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols like the David Stern on some of the graves, but criminal investigators consider this an attempt to obscure the motive of the extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is in any way related to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shaken" by the news of the grave desecration that took place as the religious month of Muslim Ramadan is drawing to a close.
At the same time, a round of conscience research is underway in Austria after the country slipped to the right in yesterday's parliamentary election.
The FPÖ and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties who received almost 30% of the vote, campaigned for a strict anti-immigrant law in their election campaign and some of their election slogans were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the FPÖ, which won 18% of the votes, campaigned for a ban on headscarves and burqas and even made his aversion to food, which is generally associated with Islam.
At his last rally in Vienna, he spoke of a "European Brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets with the argument that these are political symbols of a continuous Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses conducted immediately after the election, which state that the extreme right is the politically strongest bloc in the country, suggest that this new development is based on young voters who are worried about their future in the European Union.
