`Car bee' that avoids collisions
To drive the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature, more precisely, by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight is due to the swarm behavior of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in the technologies for accident prevention.
The engineers from the Nissan Motor Co. Technical Development Center developed this small robot in cooperation with Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the prestigious University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the head of technology PR and R&D brand management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid the collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped flight space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the facet eyes of the bee, which can see in all directions over an angle of 300 degrees, this allows you to fly undisturbed in their personal airspace without interruption.
In order to replicate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
He notices obstacles that are in front of the BR23C at a distance of up to two meters and are within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor, which is directly translated into signal for avoiding the collision
`At the moment when obstacle is noticed, the small robot will mimic the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at 90o or even greater angle to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference to other arbitrary systems is that this evasive maneuver takes place absolutely instinctively.
If it were not so, the robot might not be able to respond with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,’ explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Laboratory of Mobility and the lead engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate upwards or downwards, but also not over-corner; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in infinite ways, as the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and braking functions, so that the small robot avoids the collisions.
`This device only needs to process the information every one few seconds and act according to this information.
It does not require either the information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers to store, so it can continuously work with only a few dozens of KB of the storage space.
This sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs and not even about the MBs of storage space.
This is the first step in the development of the technologies for the immediate prevention of the collisions, a technology that Nissan predicts to introduce to the production cars over the next decade.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite to lead to the destination while driving, avoiding the obstacles along the way.
