Talk - From the blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th yesterday. anniversary of its founding, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And most importantly, she has regained the public's trust, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross' blood donation service were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry led by Judge Horace Krever in February 1994, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to work out guidelines to prevent a renewed catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to deliver his report, at the time several provinces set up a committee whose aim was to develop a new system for managing canned blood in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood preservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of the blood preserves and by working in this field during the following years, we have regained the trust of the public,' she says,' she says, before proudly stressing that in early 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. However, Décary maintains in the awareness that `trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its founding on 28. September 1998 Hema-Quebec acts on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new species of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman, who has been in charge since its foundation in 1998.
And we had not the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted via the blood.
So we invoked one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which one applies exclusion measures if one does not know this and when a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is manifested by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, it was proved without any doubt that this disease is transmitted via the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has quite meaning.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique appeared on the market for detecting HIV: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which make it possible to detect the occurrence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibody to the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize this, was substantially reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, that means you would have to distribute 12 million blood preserves before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood preserves each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs where HIV was transmitted via a blood preserve.
I believe that nowadays you can feel comfortable when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health," says Hema-Quebec's director.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, just like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects via the blood.
We need to continuously monitor,' Dr. Décary away before stressing that Hema-Quebec must also provide sufficient supply in addition to a safe supply.
`The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
