Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its issue of 17. September Le Devoir published a letter from Mr Patrick J. Garver, Vice Director General of Canada's Barrick Gold Mine.
This confirms, and in doing so pursues an Orwellian logic that the world’s largest gold-producing society sought a defamation lawsuit for six million against three authors and a small destitute publishing house, with the aim of opening a ‘public transparent debate’.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of defamation lawsuits, but on the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to drive anyone into ruin who dares to take one of their opposite opinion.
No matter how the trial ends, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid for from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
Moreover, the tactic in these unequal struggles is often to ruin the defenders in order to force a consensual settlement that silences the other side and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things before public opinion.
In contrast, what is commonplace in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually played out through the exchange of ideas rather than through club blows.
So it would have sufficed if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams that could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and brushes aside the petitions and letters in support of Noir Canada's authors with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can simultaneously ask for a `public' debate and, in doing so, disregard the opinions of this very public?
Seemingly, in the world of the Vice President, this word includes only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a quite narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public, which supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada, does so mainly because it rejects the gold mine's brutal stance.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag lawsuit (in the course of the `public debate', Barrick Gold has just made a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, in which it requires them to stop using this term...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's complaint is a direct attack on freedom to academic research and truth-finding, which is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to explore and discuss topics that the rich companies of this world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could have it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long known how to get to grips with debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it pretends, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the university world, just as it is for public debate, and it is time for governments to take action that restricts this kind of unjustified lawsuits.
