The psychology of outbidding - or why we're willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue what is offered.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the Science magazine, people do not want to be defeated in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was supposed to play the lottery while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cortex, was measured in the case of losers of the auction, in which the overbidding of the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore said that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
To support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also conducted studies on the tracking of money.
In this case, three groups should bid against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was told the true value of the product, after which they made their stakes.
Another group was also promised $15 rewards in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a losing match.
So the difference between the two groups was merely that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was losing.
As proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the group playing "against losing" were ready for higher stakes than those in the control or the "profit" group.
“These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, these have so far only justified the behaviours observed at auctions with the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, professor of the University of New York's economics faculty.
Hepatitis: When to visit the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated at a hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, however, the pathogens and the diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example, by contaminated food or water), in the case of hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travelers are recommended a vaccination against the viruses A and B anyway, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A show up about two-three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and the recovery can last for up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million dies annually. People on the far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and cirrhosis, triggered by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that only one in ten infected people is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this condition is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of people suffering from chronic hepatitis C is estimated at 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease is already detectable during a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Detected in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, which eliminates the risk of infection and prevents the development of cancer.
The 30. September is the World Hepatitis Day, hosted for the first time by patient representatives worldwide in 2004.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this virus-induced chronic liver inflammation, its emergence and the importance of early detection.
