Export prices were 1.1 percent higher than those in July 2008, and are down 3.9% from the previous year's prices.
Due to domestic price changes and the export sector, production prices were 0.7% higher than in the previous month, and 3.2 percent higher than in 2007.
Domestic selling prices are only slightly, i.e. by 0.1 percent, compared to the previous month.
Manufacturing industry's selling prices also rose little - 0.1 percent -- since July.
The biggest price increase in August 2008 was in leather goods (2.8 percent) - primarily for bags and belts - here the increase was 4.6 percent, for shoes the prices went up by 2.5 percent.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials drove up prices in chemicals and productions considerably (1.6 percent).
A price decline was recorded in crude oil processing (1.4 percent), electrical and technical equipment (0.9 percent), and slightly in wood processing (0.1 percent).
The prices in paper production, as well as at the publishers and in the printing industry remained unchanged.
In other branches of the manufacturing industry, a price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 percent was measured.
In the important domestic sales markets of the industry, such as electricity, gas, steam and water, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, primarily as a result of the one on the 1st. July introduced price increase in gas.
Looking at the domestic sales markets of the manufacturing industry year-on-year, prices in crude oil processing have risen the most (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector, a 13.2 percent increase was observed, while the increase was 11 percent in the production of food, beverages, and tobacco.
A fall in prices was observed in the textile industry (2.5 percent) and in electrical and technical equipment (0.3 percent).
The magnitude of inflation in the other manufacturing industries was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry climbed 10.2 percent last year.
Electricity, gas, steam and water prices rose by 18.7 percent year-on-year.
In the domestic sales market, the highest price increase (0.7 percent) was recorded in the fixed assets sector in August.
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices went up 0.3 percent, while they have remained the same in the energy and processing sectors compared to the previous month.
The largest price increase in August 2008 was observed in the energy and reuse sector compared to the comparable period of 2007 (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods manufacturing sectors, a price increase of 6.8 percent was noted, while a price reduction of 1.4 percent was noted for fixed assets.
Industry export prices measured in Forint rose by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, but there was a decrease of 3.9 percent year-on-year.
The domestic currency became 1.7 percent weaker compared to the euro, the dollar by 7.1 percent, and compared to the August 2007 rate, it became 7.5 percent stronger compared to the euro, and even 15.9 percent stronger in the dollar.
