Fox in the chicken coop
Due to a person’s medication consumption, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to sign a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear the data market could become uncontrollable.
“There are data protection programs that in any case link the use of the drug data to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the fox to the chickens" - quotes the Washington Post Richard Dick, developer of the program for tracking prescription data.
Insurance companies determine the fees and the withdrawal amounts in the event of damage depending on the health status of the customer, and if the risk is estimated too high, the insurance is not taken out in the first place.
Previously, the customer was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the knowledge of the investigation results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a far more favorable method: Based on the identification number of the customer, he obtains the data of the last one and a half years from the pharmacies, i.e. which preparations were bought, and the program calculates from which disease the customer suffers from and what his health condition is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it would be possible to conclude that his blood lipid levels are untreatably high, which would automatically rank him into a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so that the insurance companies only have to do the paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many medications can be taken for various purposes, such as migraines and hot flashes, but also for depression.
The latter is a high-risk factor from the point of view of the insurers, while those mentioned before that are not.
For the consultation and processing of the data, own companies have formed, which, before they obtain the data, ask the patient for his consent.
In the meantime, they have to do so by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory examinations and connect them to the data on drug use. In this way, they provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of the patients.
More and more companies have access to the data, and controlling their use is becoming more difficult.
While there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect only extends to service providers in the health sector and insurance.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing firms.
Dick Richard sees that this is too little, so he wants to further develop his program, so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question, of course, is that the data subject can hardly prohibit access to his data, otherwise the insurance companies do not conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are left to the grace of the fox.
