The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already revealed itself a few days ago, when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House's $700 billion austerity package: A large proportion of Americans were and are more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s issue of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis in the running step divides the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which always favored the state institutions and the business community, and those neoconservatives who are hostile to those in Washington and the financial world, and who, above all, win voters in the south and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise, above all, to the voice of what I mentioned above.
However, this example just mentioned is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake is announcing or even already representing: not only in the USA, but also in the entire West and perhaps beyond these will be affected by them.
In both the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the long-feared events that finally take shape and come to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unheard-of renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis means a decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage a tremendous amount of the assets of private households living in a single state.
This means a direct political problem for governments: namely, how to behave towards the families concerned, which also represent an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis thus appears economically global, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have become sidelined in itself and lost its right to speak: the obvious proof of this has been given by the EU, which, because of its division into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and above all. Distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the USA has been in the economic situation to save itself without outside help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two conditions that cannot be overvalued – in certain circumstances – which otherwise no international organization and no market will be able to fall back in a similar way.
Moreover, the new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance that has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is precisely when we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked empire, into a realm of ever differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we must suddenly realize how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
Although these can certainly all be transported from one place to the other of the world, they are nevertheless connected to the utmost with a narrowly circumscribed piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such territory, to another living in a ready-earner, waterless or oil depositary area, is in advantage.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short insertion.
Who says territory, who government, who says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis appears to be creating two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leadership, i.e. the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of economics, which have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a sense, still disturbing aspect: a loss of trust, an intolerantness, a picture of inexpediency, a sense of distance, all of which are directed at a whole class of managers of Western countries.
It seems to be the conviction among large parts of the population that it is not only the deeds of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content presents itself to the majority as increasingly foreign and more traditional.
The demand for leadership thus feeds underground a branching but powerful movement of disempowerment of the leading class and the conventional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of voters and in the sudden shift of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the Conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, about the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, towards the rebellion of American MPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
One gains the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, more and more understanding problems and therefore less representative value in terms of what is going on in the lower social classes of the West today and is reinforced by the financial crisis and driven to the point of oversizedness.
In view of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
However, keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
