Medicines: Never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, especially in the summer, can cause serious health damage if taken at the same time with certain vital medications, since they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points out the risk of packaged as well as fresh fruit juices associated with medication intake. Within the framework of the 236. Meetings of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again sounded the alarm: A glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is enough to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to such an extent that they are virtually eliminated and thus the health of the patients is endangered.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs, such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
MEDICATIONS IN JEOPY – The same agency of the drug had warned doctors and patients in a report two years ago about the dangers of this mix, and emphasizes to pay attention to what is drunk in conjunction with agents such as diazepane or metadone.
It’s not just GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active ingredients inhibited by the fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, the director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers who are thus free to change the consumer information.
Therefore, it is advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still uncertainties, not to be afraid to ask a pharmacist or doctor," emphasizes the expert of the Ansa agency.
