This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, means death for the single-room cinema in the centre in the long run. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the features of a cultural crime.
Affected are mostly historical places full of memories, "it's like losing a friend with whom you have covered a piece of road full of emotions," according to the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso," who earned him the Oscar and the Cannes Grand Prix 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever.
