When the energy springs from the waves, suddenly the big ones run up
It is a non-drying source of money that covers over 70% of the surface of the planet and only now do the world’s great energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking to occupy, such as giants such as Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and studied for 70 years; not coincidentally, these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now the environmental organizations and the increased price of oil are pushing for new impulses in the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy demand could be met by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are also the currents and tides.
Giants in attack.
The first company to now rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy sector are relying on marine energy production.
“Chevron is investigating these technologies,” according to the spokesperson for a company known to the U.S. giant in the Wall Street Journal, and weighs the opportunity to work with us.”
It is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is needed to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a not to be underestimated sign, especially considering that oil is still being extracted by the U.S. in Alaska and President Bush was just recently starting plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; if the details are also not known, observers speak of a rising interest.
Still needing improvement technologies.
Experts speak of a technology still in the making of its way, not least because the last doubts have not yet been clarified by the environmentalists.
So far, projects such as the one in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a much greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are different possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned facilities of this kind, which are only waiting for the state approval. Some of the energy generated could also serve for military facilities.
Verdant Power, meanwhile, is already producing energy for a department store and a parking lot using submarine turbines in New York's East River.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feeds the generator as a result of the rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of possible clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Power Generation Research, a special interest immediately deserves the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also waves, and therefore a more trustworthy power source.
It is precisely tidal energy that caused states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, to invest $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
